1 Robust Poisson regression

Although GEEs are used for clustered data, the package gee can also be used for robust regression with just one observation per subject.

1.1 Run the code below. Then fit the Poisson glm with overdispersion and response Cases with c_households, c_nohs, c_uninsured, c_vacant, and logPop100k as an offset, where c_households is centered households (the same model as in HW3, 1.13). Then fit the GEE model with the same covariates using gee::gee. Hint: create a variable id as 1:nrow(dat) to use as a clustering variable, with just one observation per cluster.

hiv_cases = read.csv('AtlasPlusTableData_HIV_2016.csv')
socdet = read.csv('AtlasPlusTableData_SocialDeterminants_2016.csv')
library(tidyr)
socdet_wide = socdet%>%pivot_wider(names_from = Indicator, values_from=Percent)
dat = merge(hiv_cases,socdet_wide)
dat$Pop100k = dat$Cases/dat$Rate.per.100000
dat$logPop100k = log(dat$Pop100k)
dat$c_households = scale(dat$`Households living below the federal poverty level`,scale = FALSE)
dat$c_nohs = scale(dat$`Population 25 years and older w/o HS diploma`,scale = FALSE)
dat$c_uninsured = scale(dat$Uninsured,scale = FALSE)
dat$c_vacant = scale(dat$`Vacant housing`,scale=FALSE)
hw3.model6 = glm(Cases~c_households+c_nohs+c_uninsured+c_vacant,
                 offset = log(Pop100k),data=dat,family=quasipoisson)

summary(hw3.model6)

The t-statistics from glm are slightly larger than the robust z from gee, except for intercept.

The fitted versus residual plot is used to check the linearity assumption and homoscedasticity. The blue line is not flat, which indicates a violation of the linearity assumption. The residuals are more spread out for large fitted values, indicating a violation of homoscedasticity.

plot(hw2.model1.8, sqrt(abs(resid(.))) ~ fitted(.), type = c("p", "smooth"),
     xlab = "Fitted", ylab = "Square Root of Residual")

The scale-location plot is used to check the homoscedasticity. The blue line is not flat, which indicates a violation of homoscedasticity.

2.2 What is the ICC?

# extract tau^2 and sigma^2
tau2 <- VarCorr(hw2.model1.8)$id[1]
sigma2 <- summary(hw2.model1.8)$sigma^2

# compute icc
icc <- tau2 / (tau2 + sigma2)
print(icc)
## [1] 0.2083146

The ICC is 0.2083146.

2.5 What is the test statistic for Acquisition MB=8 in the gee with exchangeable working correlation structure? How does it compare to the linear mixed model? (Note: the Wald statistic in geepack::geeglm corresponds to the robust variance estimator).

summary(model2.3)$coefficients['AcquisitionMB.8',]
##                 Estimate Std.err  Wald  Pr(>|W|)
## AcquisitionMB.8  -0.3098 0.04908 39.83 2.774e-10
summary(hw2.model1.8)$coefficients['AcquisitionMB.8',]
##   Estimate Std. Error         df    t value   Pr(>|t|) 
## -3.098e-01  5.087e-02  2.375e+02 -6.089e+00  4.525e-09

The test statistic for Acquisition MB=8 in the gee with exchangeable working correlation structure is 39.83, which is larger than the square of the t-statistic from linear mixed model: \(39.83 > (-6.089)^2\).

2.7 Let \(i\) denote participant and \(j\) denote sample, here coinciding with single-band 2 mm (\(j=1\)), multiband=12 (\(j=2\)), multiband 2 (\(j=3\)), , \(j=9\) corresponds to SB.3.3.mm. What is \(Corr(y_{i1},y_{i8})\) according to this model? What is \(Corr(y_{i2},y_{i9})\)?

\(Corr(y_{i1},y_{i8})\) = 0.4098; \(Corr(y_{i2},y_{i9})\) = 0.2847.

2.8 Use geepack::QIC to select between the exchangeable and unstructured correlation structure. QIC is interpreted in the same way as AIC. (Some authors have criticized QIC, but others have argued it is useful.) For more information about QIC, see Pan 2001 in the Readings, where QIC is defined in equation 8. Which working correlation is preferred?

library(geepack)
qic_exch <- QIC(model2.3)['QIC']
qic_unstr <- QIC(model2.6)['QIC']
qic_exch
##  QIC 
## 41.1
qic_unstr
##  QIC 
## 38.7

The QIC is 41.071 for the model with exchangeable correlation structure and 38.699 for the model with unstructured correlation structure. A smaller QIC value indicates a better fit. Thus, the unstructured correlation structure is preferred.

In this problem, we will analyze a dataset from a randomized control trial with 80 women. We are interested in predicting health status (good or poor) controlling for age group and time and including an interaction between age group and treatment.

library(readr)
library(dplyr)

health = case_when(health=='Poor'~0, TRUE ~ 1),
agegroup = factor(agegroup),
treatment = factor(txt, levels = c("Control","Intervention")),
time_months = case_when(time == 1 ~ 0, time == 2 ~ 3, time == 3 ~ 6, TRUE ~ 12), time = factor(time))

model3.1 <- glmer(health ~ time_months + treatment + agegroup +
                   treatment:agegroup + (1|id),

3.3 What is the odds ratio and 95% confidence interval for treatment=Intervention in age group 25-34 versus Control in age group 25-34?

coefs = summary(model3.2)$coefficients
coef_inter = coefs['treatmentIntervention', 'Estimate']
coef_age25_34_inter = coefs['treatmentIntervention:agegroup25-34', 'Estimate']
odds_ratio = exp(coef_inter + coef_age25_34_inter)
odds_ratio
## [1] 1.72
cov_odds <- coefs['treatmentIntervention', 'Std. Error']^2 + 
            coefs['treatmentIntervention:agegroup25-34', 'Std. Error']^2 +
            2 * vcov(model3.2)["treatmentIntervention",
                               "treatmentIntervention:agegroup25-34"] 
            
(lower = exp(coef_inter + coef_age25_34_inter - 1.96 * sqrt(cov_odds)))
## [1] 0.378
(upper = exp(coef_inter + coef_age25_34_inter + 1.96 * sqrt(cov_odds)))
## [1] 7.78

The odds ratio is 1.715, and 95% confidence interval is (0.378, 7.777).

3.4 Write out a gee model with outcome health, predictors treatment, agegroup, treatment*agegroup, and time_months, and exchangeable working correlation. Note: you can adapt this latex code \[R_i = \pmatrix{1 & a & b & c \\ d & 1 & e & f \\ g & h & 1 & i \\ j & k & l & 1}.\]

Let \(y_{ij}\) be the health outcome of subject \(i\) at months \(j\) and \(\textbf{y}_i = (y_{i1}, y_{i2}, \cdots, y_{ij})\) be the vector of health outcomes for subject \(i\),

\[ y_{ij} \sim Bernoulli(p_{ij})\\ logit(p_{ij}) = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}*\text{months}_{ij}+ \beta_{2}*I(Treatment_{ij}=Intervention) + \beta_{3}*I(age_{ij}=25-34)+ \beta_{4}*I(age_{ij}=35+) + \\ \beta_{5}*I(Treatment_{ij}=Intervention)*I(age_{ij}=25-34) + \beta_{6} * I(Treatment_{ij}=Intervention)*I(age_{ij}=35+) \\ Cov(\textbf{y}_i) = \phi \textbf{D}_i^{1/2} \textbf{R}_i (\alpha) \textbf{D}_i^{1/2} \] where \(\phi\) is the scale parameter; \(\textbf{D}_i\) is diagonal matrix where the \(j^{th}\) diagonal element \(\textbf{D}_{i, [j,j]} = p_{ij} \times (1 - p_{ij})\), representing the marginal variance; and

\[ \textbf{R}_i(\alpha) = \pmatrix{1 & \alpha & \alpha & \alpha \\ \alpha & 1 & \alpha & \alpha \\ \alpha & \alpha & 1 & \alpha \\ \alpha & \alpha & \alpha & 1}. \]

3.10 Does age group modify the effect of treatment? State the null hypothesis, conduct a statistical test, and state your conclusion. Use the AR1 working correlation structure.

# Fit the GEE model with AR1 working correlation
model3.10 <- geeglm(health ~ treatment + agegroup + time_months,
                   data = health,
                   id = id,
                   family = binomial,
                   corstr = "ar1")

anova(model3.10, model3.7)
## Analysis of 'Wald statistic' Table
## 
## Model 1 health ~ treatment + agegroup + treatment:agegroup + time_months 
## Model 2 health ~ treatment + agegroup + time_months
##   Df   X2 P(>|Chi|)
## 1  2 2.06      0.36

\(H_0\): age group does not modify the effect of treatment (\(\beta_5\) = \(\beta_6\) =0).

The p-value of the test is 0.36 > 0.05. We fail to reject null hypothesis and conclude that age group does not significantly modify the effect of treatment.
